Firmicus 11 ll 3, if his astrological jargon is translated into astronomical equivalents, will be found to give the same table of degi-ees, assigning it, like Manilius, to the latitude not of Rhodes but of Alexandria (and, says hc, of Babylon). Martianus Capella 844-5, not specifying his latitude, gives a very similar table of hours, in which the shortest time (Aries Pisces lh. 20 m.) and the longest (Virgo Libra 211. 40 m.) coincide with Manilius’ account, but the inter-vals differ from his, in that some of them consist of more than 16 m. and some of less.
